  "tutorial/query-params-str-validations::section-0004": {
    "node_id": "tutorial/query-params-str-validations::section-0004",
    "parent_id": "tutorial/query-params-str-validations::section-0001",
    "level": 2,
    "node_kind": "heading",
    "heading_text": "Use Annotated in the type for the q parameter",
    "anchor_id": "use-annotated-in-the-type-for-the-q-parameter",
    "section_url": "https://fastapi.tiangolo.com/tutorial/query-params-str-validations/#use-annotated-in-the-type-for-the-q-parameter",
    "section_text": "Remember I told you before that Annotated can be used to add metadata to your parameters in the Python Types Intro ?\n\nNow it's the time to use it with FastAPI. 🚀\n\nWe had this type annotation:\n\nWhat we will do is wrap that with Annotated , so it becomes:\n\nBoth of those versions mean the same thing, q is a parameter that can be a str or None , and by default, it is None .\n\nNow let's jump to the fun stuff. 🎉",
    "section_inline_code": [
      "Annotated",
      "q",
      "str",
      "None"
    ],
    "section_links": [
      {
        "text": "Python Types Intro",
        "url": "../python-types.md#type-hints-with-metadata-annotations",
        "section_id": "tutorial/query-params-str-validations::section-0004",
        "section_url": "https://fastapi.tiangolo.com/tutorial/query-params-str-validations/#use-annotated-in-the-type-for-the-q-parameter"
      }
    ],
    "code_refs": [],
    "code_blocks": [
      {
        "type": "code_block",
        "language": "Python",
        "text": "q: str | None = None",
        "section_id": "tutorial/query-params-str-validations::section-0004",
        "section_url": "https://fastapi.tiangolo.com/tutorial/query-params-str-validations/#use-annotated-in-the-type-for-the-q-parameter"
      },
      {
        "type": "code_block",
        "language": "Python",
        "text": "q: Annotated[str | None] = None",
        "section_id": "tutorial/query-params-str-validations::section-0004",
        "section_url": "https://fastapi.tiangolo.com/tutorial/query-params-str-validations/#use-annotated-in-the-type-for-the-q-parameter"
      }
    ]
  },
  "tutorial/query-params-str-validations::section-0005": {
    "node_id": "tutorial/query-params-str-validations::section-0005",
    "parent_id": "tutorial/query-params-str-validations::section-0001",
    "level": 2,
    "node_kind": "heading",
    "heading_text": "Add Query to Annotated in the q parameter",
    "anchor_id": "add-query-to-annotated-in-the-q-parameter",
    "section_url": "https://fastapi.tiangolo.com/tutorial/query-params-str-validations/#add-query-to-annotated-in-the-q-parameter",
    "section_text": "Now that we have this Annotated where we can put more information (in this case some additional validation), add Query inside of Annotated , and set the parameter max_length to 50 :\n\nNotice that the default value is still None , so the parameter is still optional.\n\nBut now, having Query(max_length=50) inside of Annotated , we are telling FastAPI that we want it to have additional validation for this value, we want it to have maximum 50 characters. 😎\n\nFastAPI will now:\n\n- Validate the data making sure that the max length is 50 characters\n\n- Show a clear error for the client when the data is not valid\n\n- Document the parameter in the OpenAPI schema path operation (so it will show up in the automatic docs UI )",
    "section_inline_code": [
      "Query",
      "Annotated",
      "q",
      "max_length",
      "50",
      "None",
      "Query(max_length=50)"
    ],
    "section_links": [],
    "code_refs": [
      {
        "type": "code_ref",
        "path": "../../docs_src/query_params_str_validations/tutorial002_an_py310.py",
        "highlight_lines": [
          9
        ],
        "raw": "{* ../../docs_src/query_params_str_validations/tutorial002_an_py310.py hl[9] *}",
        "section_id": "tutorial/query-params-str-validations::section-0005",
        "section_url": "https://fastapi.tiangolo.com/tutorial/query-params-str-validations/#add-query-to-annotated-in-the-q-parameter"
      }
    ],
    "code_blocks": []
  },
  "tutorial/query-params-str-validations::section-0006": {
    "node_id": "tutorial/query-params-str-validations::section-0006",
    "parent_id": "tutorial/query-params-str-validations::section-0001",
    "level": 2,
    "node_kind": "heading",
    "heading_text": "Alternative (old): Query as the default value",
    "anchor_id": "alternative-old-query-as-the-default-value",
    "section_url": "https://fastapi.tiangolo.com/tutorial/query-params-str-validations/#alternative-old-query-as-the-default-value",
    "section_text": "Previous versions of FastAPI (before 0.95.0 ) required you to use Query as the default value of your parameter, instead of putting it in Annotated , there's a high chance that you will see code using it around, so I'll explain it to you.\n\nThis is how you would use Query() as the default value of your function parameter, setting the parameter max_length to 50:\n\nAs in this case (without using Annotated ) we have to replace the default value None in the function with Query() , we now need to set the default value with the parameter Query(default=None) , it serves the same purpose of defining that default value (at least for FastAPI).\n\nSo:\n\n...makes the parameter optional, with a default value of None , the same as:\n\nBut the Query version declares it explicitly as being a query parameter.\n\nThen, we can pass more parameters to Query . In this case, the max_length parameter that applies to strings:\n\nThis will validate the data, show a clear error when the data is not valid, and document the parameter in the OpenAPI schema path operation .",
    "section_inline_code": [
      "Query",
      "Annotated",
      "Query()",
      "max_length",
      "None",
      "Query(default=None)"
    ],
    "section_links": [],
    "code_refs": [
      {
        "type": "code_ref",
        "path": "../../docs_src/query_params_str_validations/tutorial002_py310.py",
        "highlight_lines": [
          7
        ],
        "raw": "{* ../../docs_src/query_params_str_validations/tutorial002_py310.py hl[7] *}",
        "section_id": "tutorial/query-params-str-validations::section-0006",
        "section_url": "https://fastapi.tiangolo.com/tutorial/query-params-str-validations/#alternative-old-query-as-the-default-value"
      }
    ],
    "code_blocks": [
      {
        "type": "code_block",
        "language": "Python",
        "text": "q: str | None = Query(default=None)",
        "section_id": "tutorial/query-params-str-validations::section-0006",
        "section_url": "https://fastapi.tiangolo.com/tutorial/query-params-str-validations/#alternative-old-query-as-the-default-value"
      },
      {
        "type": "code_block",
        "language": "Python",
        "text": "q: str | None = None",
        "section_id": "tutorial/query-params-str-validations::section-0006",
        "section_url": "https://fastapi.tiangolo.com/tutorial/query-params-str-validations/#alternative-old-query-as-the-default-value"
      },
      {
        "type": "code_block",
        "language": "Python",
        "text": "q: str | None = Query(default=None, max_length=50)",
        "section_id": "tutorial/query-params-str-validations::section-0006",
        "section_url": "https://fastapi.tiangolo.com/tutorial/query-params-str-validations/#alternative-old-query-as-the-default-value"
      }
    ]
  },
  "tutorial/query-params-str-validations::section-0007": {
    "node_id": "tutorial/query-params-str-validations::section-0007",
    "parent_id": "tutorial/query-params-str-validations::section-0006",
    "level": 3,
    "node_kind": "heading",
    "heading_text": "Query as the default value or in Annotated",
    "anchor_id": "query-as-the-default-value-or-in-annotated",
    "section_url": "https://fastapi.tiangolo.com/tutorial/query-params-str-validations/#query-as-the-default-value-or-in-annotated",
    "section_text": "Keep in mind that when using Query inside of Annotated you cannot use the default parameter for Query .\n\nInstead, use the actual default value of the function parameter. Otherwise, it would be inconsistent.\n\nFor example, this is not allowed:\n\n...because it's not clear if the default value should be \"rick\" or \"morty\" .\n\nSo, you would use (preferably):\n\n...or in older code bases you will find:",
    "section_inline_code": [
      "Query",
      "Annotated",
      "default",
      "\"rick\"",
      "\"morty\""
    ],
    "section_links": [],
    "code_refs": [],
    "code_blocks": [
      {
        "type": "code_block",
        "language": "Python",
        "text": "q: Annotated[str, Query(default=\"rick\")] = \"morty\"",
        "section_id": "tutorial/query-params-str-validations::section-0007",
        "section_url": "https://fastapi.tiangolo.com/tutorial/query-params-str-validations/#query-as-the-default-value-or-in-annotated"
      },
      {
        "type": "code_block",
        "language": "Python",
        "text": "q: Annotated[str, Query()] = \"rick\"",
        "section_id": "tutorial/query-params-str-validations::section-0007",
        "section_url": "https://fastapi.tiangolo.com/tutorial/query-params-str-validations/#query-as-the-default-value-or-in-annotated"
      },
      {
        "type": "code_block",
        "language": "Python",
        "text": "q: str = Query(default=\"rick\")",
        "section_id": "tutorial/query-params-str-validations::section-0007",
        "section_url": "https://fastapi.tiangolo.com/tutorial/query-params-str-validations/#query-as-the-default-value-or-in-annotated"
      }
    ]
  },
  "tutorial/query-params-str-validations::section-0008": {
    "node_id": "tutorial/query-params-str-validations::section-0008",
    "parent_id": "tutorial/query-params-str-validations::section-0006",
    "level": 3,
    "node_kind": "heading",
    "heading_text": "Advantages of Annotated",
    "anchor_id": "advantages-of-annotated",
    "section_url": "https://fastapi.tiangolo.com/tutorial/query-params-str-validations/#advantages-of-annotated",
    "section_text": "Using Annotated is recommended instead of the default value in function parameters, it is better for multiple reasons. 🤓\n\nThe default value of the function parameter is the actual default value, that's more intuitive with Python in general. 😌\n\nYou could call that same function in other places without FastAPI, and it would work as expected . If there's a required parameter (without a default value), your editor will let you know with an error, Python will also complain if you run it without passing the required parameter.\n\nWhen you don't use Annotated and instead use the (old) default value style , if you call that function without FastAPI in other places , you have to remember to pass the arguments to the function for it to work correctly, otherwise the values will be different from what you expect (e.g. QueryInfo or something similar instead of str ). And your editor won't complain, and Python won't complain running that function, only when the operations inside error out.\n\nBecause Annotated can have more than one metadata annotation, you could now even use the same function with other tools, like Typer . 🚀",
    "section_inline_code": [
      "Annotated",
      "QueryInfo",
      "str"
    ],
    "section_links": [
      {
        "text": "Typer",
        "url": "https://typer.tiangolo.com/",
        "section_id": "tutorial/query-params-str-validations::section-0008",
        "section_url": "https://fastapi.tiangolo.com/tutorial/query-params-str-validations/#advantages-of-annotated"
      }
    ],
    "code_refs": [],
    "code_blocks": []
  },
